@startuml
title Toggle Switch

participant "Ctc" as Ctc1 #90EE90# 
participant "TrackController\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \nCtc" as TrackController1 #90EE90# 

box "" #D3D3D3#
  participant "TrackModel\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \nTrackModel" as TrackModel2 #90EE90#  
  participant "Block\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \nBlock" as Block4 #90EE90#   
end box  

rectangle "#FFFFFF#" {    
    note right of TrackModel2 : getSwitch() -> setSwitchState("normal"\nor "alternate")\non switch object in block
    
}


== Select Block ==



activate Ctc1 


deactivate Ctc1 



' There's a return arrow here from select block to CTC - not sure how this works?




autonumber "<b>[0]"  


setSwitchStatus(Block,direction) --> activate TrackController1  





ref over TrackController1 , TrackModel2 ** Set direction on track model** 




setSwitchStatus(Block,direction)->> +TrackModel2    







getblock()->>+Block4     






note left of Block4 <u>**Get the correct switch for our current location.**</u>\nThe active controller will always be associated with one particular block at any given time.\nWe can use that information along with data about which way we want things pointed,\nto figure out what state should actually go into effect next...








new_switch_status <-[dotted] deactivate TrackModel2      










update_Switch_Status(block,status)<-[hidden]-+trackcontroller1        









Note Right Of trackmodel,bottomright:<font color=black><i>"Normal"</I></Font>&nbsp;&nbsp;<--->&nbsp;<<FONT COLOR = BLACK >< I >Alternate </ i ></ font >>\\<br/>These represent two different states where trains could potentially travel through depending upon their destination requirements etcetera..."













@enduml